hares, or zero shares, because the denominator was artificially inflated.","Redeem the attacker's shares after the victim deposit to recover the donation and extract the victim's lost value."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Anyone can steal approved VISR by depositing from another user's address and minting shares to themselves","locations":["contracts/RewardsHypervisor.sol:41","contracts/RewardsHypervisor.sol:43","contracts/RewardsHypervisor.sol:47","contracts/RewardsHypervisor.sol:48","contracts/RewardsHypervisor.sol:60","contracts/RewardsHypervisor.sol:61","contracts/RewardsHypervisor.sol:64"],"claim":"On the EOA path, `deposit()` never requires `msg.sender == from`. It simply calls `visr.safeTransferFrom(from, address(this), visrDeposit)` and then mints the resulting vVISR to arbitrary `to`. Therefore, any caller can spend another user's VISR allowance to the Hypervisor and route the newly minted shares to themselves.","impact":"Any user who has approved the Hypervisor to spend VISR, which is the normal prerequisite for depositing, can have that approved VISR pulled into the pool by an attacker. The attacker receives the vVISR shares and can immediately redeem them, turning ordinary allowances into direct theft.","paths":["A victim approves the Hypervisor to spend their VISR so they can deposit later.","An attacker calls `deposit(amount, victim, attacker)` while the approval is still active.","The Hypervisor transfers VISR from the victim via `safeTransferFrom` and mints vVISR shares to the attacker.","The attacker keeps the shares or calls `withdraw()` to extract the corresponding VISR value."],"round":1,"source_agents":["merge_review"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Unprotected Mint and Burn Functions in vVISR","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected: `vVISR` defines its own `owner` storage, initializes it in the constructor, and gates `mint()`/`burn()` with a functioning custom `onlyOwner` modifier."},{"title":"Share Calculation Uses Post-Transfer Balance Without Verification","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected: the share calculation happens before either transfer branch executes, not after; the real reportable issue is the unverified contract-path transfer, which is already covered by F-001."},{"title":"Missing Validation for Share Burning in Withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected: `withdraw()` requires `from == msg.sender` or `IVisor(from).owner() == msg.sender`, and `vVISR.burn()` is intentionally callable only by the token owner contract."},{"title":"Inconsistent Compiler Version and Missing License","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected: outdated compiler choice and license metadata are not protocol-level vulnerabilities in this codebase."},{"title":"Deposits are priced from the requested amount instead of the actual VISR received","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"Not kept as a separate finding: the concrete exploitably supported portion is the contract-path under-transfer/no-transfer bug, which is merged into F-001; broader fee-on-transfer or rebasing assumptions about the configured VISR token are too speculative here."}]}
